<section>
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Setup</h2>
        <div class="steps">
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>Download Claude Desktop</h4>
                    <p>Go to <a href="https://claude.ai/download">claude.ai/download</a> and install it on your computer. It works on Mac and Windows.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>Open Claude</h4>
                    <p>Launch the app. You'll see a chat window — just like texting, but with AI.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>Try a prompt</h4>
                    <p>Type something and press Enter. Start with something simple from the examples below.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container">
        <h2>First Prompts to Try</h2>
        <p>Start with these. No setup needed — just paste into Claude and see what happens.</p>

        <div class="prompt-card open">
            <div class="prompt-card-header">
                <h4>Simplify a paragraph</h4>
                <span class="chevron">&#9660;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="prompt-card-body">
                <div class="prompt-text">
                    <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
                    <code>Make this paragraph clearer and more concise. Keep the meaning, but use simpler language:

[Paste a paragraph from a report or email you're working on]</code>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prompt-card open">
            <div class="prompt-card-header">
                <h4>Draft a quick email</h4>
                <span class="chevron">&#9660;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="prompt-card-body">
                <div class="prompt-text">
                    <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
                    <code>Draft a short internal email to my team about [topic]. Keep it under 150 words. Tone: friendly and direct.</code>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prompt-card open">
            <div class="prompt-card-header">
                <h4>Summarize something long</h4>
                <span class="chevron">&#9660;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="prompt-card-body">
                <div class="prompt-text">
                    <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
                    <code>Summarize this in 3-5 bullet points. Focus on decisions made and next steps:

[Paste meeting notes, a long email, or a document]</code>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Tips for Better Prompts</h2>

        <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-badge">1</div>
                <h4>Give context</h4>
                <p>"I'm a program director at a youth nonprofit" tells Claude how to frame its response.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-badge">2</div>
                <h4>Be specific</h4>
                <p>"Under 200 words, in bullet points, for a grant funder" is better than "make this better."</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-badge">3</div>
                <h4>Iterate</h4>
                <p>Don't accept the first output. Say "make it shorter" or "use a warmer tone" or "add more data."</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-badge">4</div>
                <h4>Give examples</h4>
                <p>"Here's a program description we like: [example]. Write something similar" gives Claude a model to follow.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

